## Usage

Install this item when building a custom billing composition. It defines the shared resource states, account references, money values, allowances, plans, subscriptions, usage, credits, activity, messages, and formatting options used by the billing blocks.

```ts
import type { BillingPlan, BillingResource } from '@/blocks/billing/billing-contracts/billing-contracts';

const plans: BillingResource<BillingPlan[]> = {
  status: 'ready',
  quality: 'authoritative',
  asOf: '2026-07-20T12:00:00.000Z',
  data: [{
    id: 'growth',
    name: 'Growth',
    prices: [{
      kind: 'fixed',
      id: 'growth-monthly',
      interval: 'month',
      money: { amountMinor: '4900', currency: 'USD' }
    }]
  }]
};
```

Keep quantities, limits, deltas, and minor-unit money as decimal strings so large values retain their precision. Supply an explicit locale and time zone to the formatters, keep each record's currency, and use the explicit contact-sales, unlimited, uninitialized, and unknown variants when they apply.

## Usage

Pass a plan resource, account context, formatting options, a controlled billing interval, and the actions you want to show.

```tsx
import { BillingPricingTable } from '@/blocks/billing/billing-pricing-table/billing-pricing-table';

<BillingPricingTable
  resource={{ status: 'ready', quality: 'authoritative', data: plans }}
  account={{ entityId: 'org_123', kind: 'organization', label: 'Northstar Labs' }}
  formatOptions={{ locale: 'en-US', timeZone: 'UTC' }}
  interval="month"
  onIntervalChange={setInterval}
  onSelectPlan={({ planId, priceId, account }) => openPlanSelection({ planId, priceId, account })}
  onContactSales={({ planId, account }) => openSalesRequest({ planId, account })}
/>
```

Fixed prices use minor-unit decimal strings and the currency on each record. Use `BillingPrice.kind = 'contact_sales'` for custom pricing. Missing callbacks remove their actions, rejected promises appear next to the action, and resolved promises leave the selected plan state under your control.

## Usage

Pass the current plan together with any payment and provider states you want to show. Add only the actions that make sense in your billing flow.

```tsx
import { BillingSubscriptionCard } from '@/blocks/billing/billing-subscription-card/billing-subscription-card';

<BillingSubscriptionCard
  resource={{
    status: 'ready',
    data: {
      id: 'sub_123',
      planId: 'growth',
      planName: 'Growth',
      status: 'active',
      renewsAt: '2026-08-01T00:00:00.000Z',
      paymentStatus: 'current',
      provider: { label: 'Connected billing provider', status: 'active' }
    }
  }}
  account={{ entityId: 'org_123', kind: 'organization' }}
  formatOptions={{ locale: 'en-US', timeZone: 'UTC' }}
  onManageSubscription={({ subscriptionId, account }) => openSubscriptionSettings(subscriptionId, account)}
/>
```

Only `renewsAt` is labelled “Renews”; `endsAt` is always labelled “Ends.” Status strings are open, unknown values render neutrally, and missing callbacks hide their controls.

## Usage

Pass each entitlement with a semantic kind so features, caps, quotas, and metered allowances keep their distinct meaning.

```tsx
import { BillingEntitlementsList } from '@/blocks/billing/billing-entitlements-list/billing-entitlements-list';

<BillingEntitlementsList
  resource={{
    status: 'ready',
    data: [
      { id: 'sso', kind: 'feature', label: 'Single sign-on', enabled: true },
      { id: 'projects', kind: 'cap', label: 'Projects', value: '25' },
      { id: 'queries', kind: 'meter', meterSlug: 'query_time', label: 'Query time', unit: 'seconds', allowance: { kind: 'limited', limit: '1000000' } }
    ]
  }}
  account={{ entityId: 'org_123', kind: 'organization' }}
  formatOptions={{ locale: 'en-US', timeZone: 'UTC' }}
/>
```

Use explicit `unlimited`, `uninitialized`, and `unknown` variants. Unknown values stay visible with a neutral presentation, and message overrides let you adapt the labels without changing the data model.

## Usage

Pass a current-period usage snapshot and nest child meters beneath category or universal pools when credits are shared.

```tsx
import { BillingUsageOverview } from '@/blocks/billing/billing-usage-overview/billing-usage-overview';

<BillingUsageOverview
  resource={{ status: 'ready', quality: 'authoritative', data: usageSnapshot }}
  account={{ entityId: 'org_123', kind: 'organization' }}
  formatOptions={{ locale: 'en-US', timeZone: 'UTC' }}
  onViewHistory={(meterSlug) => openUsageHistory(meterSlug)}
  onBuyCredits={(meterSlug) => openCreditPurchase(meterSlug)}
/>
```

Category and universal pools stay nested so their application order remains clear. Progress caps visually at 100 percent while text and accessible values preserve the actual used, allowance, and overage values. Actions disappear when their callbacks are absent.

## Usage

Pass available balances and their credit lots while keeping each meter and unit independent.

```tsx
import { BillingCreditsCard } from '@/blocks/billing/billing-credits-card/billing-credits-card';

<BillingCreditsCard
  resource={{
    status: 'ready',
    data: [{
      meterSlug: 'query_time',
      label: 'Query time',
      unit: 'seconds',
      available: '7200',
      lots: [{ id: 'lot_1', kind: 'rollover', amount: '3600', remaining: '1800', expiresAt: '2026-08-01T00:00:00.000Z' }]
    }]
  }}
  account={{ entityId: 'org_123', kind: 'organization' }}
  formatOptions={{ locale: 'en-US', timeZone: 'UTC' }}
/>
```

Keep incompatible meters and units in separate balance groups. Credit lots show the current grant makeup, while `billing-activity-table` provides a chronological view of grants, usage, adjustments, rollover, and expiration.

## Usage

Pass a page of usage periods and control the meter, period, and pagination values when you provide their callbacks.

```tsx
import { BillingUsageHistory } from '@/blocks/billing/billing-usage-history/billing-usage-history';

<BillingUsageHistory
  resource={{ status: 'ready', quality: 'estimated', data: usagePage }}
  account={{ entityId: 'org_123', kind: 'organization' }}
  formatOptions={{ locale: 'en-US', timeZone: 'UTC' }}
  meterSlug="query_time"
  period="last-6-months"
  meterOptions={meterOptions}
  periodOptions={periodOptions}
  onMeterChange={setMeterSlug}
  onPeriodChange={setPeriod}
  onPageChange={setPage}
/>
```

Credits and overage columns appear only when their values are marked as confirmed. Quality labels remain visible on each period, and the table keeps pagination and filter changes under your control.

## Usage

Pass ledger class and entry type with each activity entry so labels and badge tones describe the event itself.

```tsx
import { BillingActivityTable } from '@/blocks/billing/billing-activity-table/billing-activity-table';

<BillingActivityTable
  resource={{ status: 'ready', quality: 'authoritative', data: activityPage }}
  account={{ entityId: 'org_123', kind: 'organization' }}
  formatOptions={{ locale: 'en-US', timeZone: 'UTC' }}
  meterOptions={meterOptions}
  entryTypeOptions={entryTypeOptions}
  onMeterChange={setMeterSlug}
  onEntryTypeChange={setEntryType}
  onPageChange={setPage}
/>
```

A positive delta can represent consumption and a negative delta can represent release or reset, so presentation derives from `ledgerClass` and `entryType` rather than the sign. Unknown values remain neutral, and JSON-safe metadata opens in a titled detail sheet.

## Usage

Pass one account together with independent resources and actions. Use `section` and `onSectionChange` to synchronize navigation, or `defaultSection` for local state. The page renders its own heading by default; set `showHeader={false}` when the surrounding document already provides it.

```tsx
import { BillingSettingsPage } from '@/blocks/billing/billing-settings-page/billing-settings-page';

<BillingSettingsPage
  account={{ entityId: 'org_123', kind: 'organization', label: 'Northstar Labs' }}
  resources={{ plans, subscription, entitlements, usage, credits, usageHistory, activity }}
  actions={{
    onSelectPlan: openPlanSelection,
    onManageSubscription: openSubscriptionSettings,
    onViewHistory: openMeterHistory,
    onBuyCredits: openCreditPurchase
  }}
  formatOptions={{ locale: 'en-US', timeZone: 'UTC' }}
  section={section}
  onSectionChange={setSection}
/>
```

Each resource renders its own loading, empty, error, ready, and quality state, so one unavailable section never replaces the whole page. Controlled filters and actions are forwarded to their matching leaf blocks.

## Usage

Pass a Sheets configuration for the active application database. The feature root reads the current `_meta` contract, keeps tables with an exact application smart-tag scope, and delegates table selection, creation, and spreadsheet events to the host.

```tsx
import { DataFeaturePack } from '@/blocks/feature-packs/data/data-feature-pack';

<DataFeaturePack
  config={sheetsConfig}
  defaultActiveTable="projects"
  applicationScopes={['app']}
  onActiveTableChange={setActiveTable}
  onEvent={recordSheetEvent}
/>
```

Use `activeTable` with `onActiveTableChange` when routing owns selection. The installed sidecar describes compatibility for tooling; PostgreSQL privileges and RLS remain authoritative for every query and mutation.

This `feature-pack-data` item is provider-neutral and works without Console Kit. Install `console-module-data` when Console Kit should supply its navigation, capability discovery, and tenant runtime binding.

## Usage

Choose the entry or account view, grant each available operation through policy, and provide its matching provider callback.

```tsx
import { AuthFeaturePack } from '@/blocks/feature-packs/auth/auth-feature-pack';

<AuthFeaturePack
  view="account"
  account={account}
  notice={notice}
  passwordPolicy={{ minLength: 12 }}
  policy={{ signOut: true, changePassword: true, sendVerificationEmail: true }}
  actions={authActions}
  onError={reportAuthError}
/>
```

An action appears only when its policy grant and callback are both present. Password policy is host-defined, and complete OTP, passkey, OAuth, or TOTP implementations can be contributed through `challengeContributions` without placing challenge credentials in public component state. Callback credentials stay inside the trusted adapter boundary; the feature pack receives only token-free flow state and notices.

This `feature-pack-auth` item is provider-neutral and works without Console Kit. Install `console-module-auth` when Console Kit should supply its navigation, capability discovery, session flow, and Constructive adapter.

## Usage

Pass application members and any discovered invitation, profile, permission, default, or audit sections through one resource, then grant and inject only the access operations available to the current administrator.

```tsx
import { UsersFeaturePack } from '@/blocks/feature-packs/users/users-feature-pack';

<UsersFeaturePack
  resource={appAccess}
  policy={{ invite: true, setApproved: true, setDisabled: true, setProfile: true, setDirectPermission: true }}
  actions={appAccessActions}
  onError={reportAccessError}
/>
```

Lifecycle, owner, admin, profile, direct-permission, and default-permission changes use separate semantic actions. Invitation and member rows additionally require their own `actionPolicy`, which lets the resource mirror RLS and final-owner constraints without rendering unusable controls. The permission catalog stays read-only, effective permissions stay separate from direct grants, and `section` plus `onSectionChange` can synchronize nested navigation with a host router.

This `feature-pack-users` item keeps its stable registry ID, remains provider-neutral, and works without Console Kit. Install `console-module-users` when Console Kit should supply navigation, capability discovery, and the Constructive adapter.

## Usage

Pass one policy-filtered organization snapshot and the semantic callbacks supported by the current tenant database. Keep the active organization and optional controlled section in host state.

```tsx
import { OrganizationsFeaturePack } from '@/blocks/feature-packs/organizations/organizations-feature-pack';

<OrganizationsFeaturePack
  resource={organizations}
  policy={organizationPolicy}
  actions={organizationActions}
  section={section}
  onSectionChange={setSection}
  onError={reportOrganizationError}
/>
```

The resource can expose members, active and claimed invitations, access profiles, permissions, defaults, membership settings, hierarchy edges, principals, and API keys. Every mutation requires a pack policy grant, a matching callback, and any relevant row policy; PostgreSQL privileges and RLS remain authoritative. Treat reusable invitation tokens as secrets and display a newly created API key only from that mutation's one-time result. Because `create_org_principal` returns `user_id` while public reads may omit organization scope, fail closed and surface a limitation for an unscopable keyless principal; never infer that it belongs to the only visible organization.

This `feature-pack-organizations` item is provider-neutral and works without Console Kit. Install `console-module-organizations` when Console Kit should supply semantic routing, capability discovery, `_meta` contract resolution, and the Constructive adapter.

## Usage

Pass the policy-visible buckets, active path, and objects through resource, then inject only the file operations supported by the current database.

```tsx
import { StorageFeaturePack } from '@/blocks/feature-packs/storage/storage-feature-pack';

<StorageFeaturePack
  resource={storage}
  policy={{ selectBucket: true, navigate: true, createBucket: true, upload: true, download: true, deleteObject: true }}
  actions={storageActions}
  onError={reportStorageError}
/>
```

The host owns bucket and path state. Navigation and mutations report intent through callbacks, and the next resource value reflects the access that remains after storage policy is reapplied.

This `feature-pack-storage` item is provider-neutral and works without Console Kit. Install `console-module-storage` when Console Kit should supply its navigation, capability discovery, `_meta` contract resolver, Constructive adapter, and storage state slice.

## Usage

Pass one billing account and the independent resources for subscription, entitlements, usage, credits, history, activity, and plans. The feature root preserves the mature Billing settings page contract.

```tsx
import { BillingFeaturePack } from '@/blocks/feature-packs/billing/billing-feature-pack';

<BillingFeaturePack
  account={account}
  resources={billingResources}
  actions={billingActions}
  formatOptions={{ locale: 'en-US', timeZone: 'UTC' }}
  section={section}
  onSectionChange={setSection}
/>
```

Each resource keeps its own loading, empty, error, ready, and quality state. Omitted callbacks remove their controls, and provider operations remain outside the reusable billing view.

This `feature-pack-billing` item is provider-neutral and works without Console Kit. Install `console-module-billing` when Console Kit should supply its navigation, capability discovery, and Constructive adapter.

## Usage

Pass notifications and the authoritative unread count through resource, then grant and inject the inbox actions supported by the application.

```tsx
import { NotificationsFeaturePack } from '@/blocks/feature-packs/notifications/notifications-feature-pack';

<NotificationsFeaturePack
  resource={notifications}
  policy={{ markRead: true, markAllRead: true, openNotification: true, deleteNotification: true }}
  actions={notificationActions}
  onError={reportNotificationError}
/>
```

The all and unread filter remains local. Message content and read state stay host-controlled, so refresh the resource after a successful action and let database policy determine the resulting inbox.

This `feature-pack-notifications` item is provider-neutral and works without Console Kit. Install `console-module-notifications` when Console Kit should supply its navigation, capability discovery, and Constructive adapter.
